Fashion design is the art of applying design, aesthetics, and natural beauty to clothing and its accessories. It is influenced by cultural and social attitudes, andis constantly evolving with new trends and styles. Fashion designers use their creativity, drawing skills, and technical knowledge to create original designs for clothing, shoes, and accessories. They research current fashion trends, fabric and materials, and manufacturing techniques to bring their designsvaries across time and place.

During the 19th century, fashion became more accessible to the masses due to the industrial revolution, which made it possible to produce clothing on a largescale. The invention of the sewing machine also allowed for the creation of more detailed and intricate designs.  In the early 20th century, fashion designers such as Paul Poiret and Coco Chanel revolutionized the industry by introducing more relaxed and practical styles

Most fashion designers hold andl art and designer bachelor's degree. During a fashion design , program students study fabric's fashion theory and colour theory. They also learn how to create style's using computer -aided design (CAD) software.
